OLIVER HURT-HILLER: Policy
and advocacy is important.

00:22:05.480 --> 00:22:06.400
It's also difficult.

00:22:06.400 --> 00:22:09.195
And it may not be-- one
of the things that's

00:22:09.195 --> 00:22:11.690
made us successful, Tim
would probably tell you,

00:22:11.690 --> 00:22:15.820
is that we're sort of focused
on doing what we do really well,

00:22:15.820 --> 00:22:17.290
and not getting too distracted.

00:22:17.290 --> 00:22:19.720
But we are excited
about the idea

00:22:19.720 --> 00:22:22.460
of having an impact
beyond just direct relief.

00:22:22.460 --> 00:22:25.810
And so to your question, one of
the things we're starting to do

00:22:25.810 --> 00:22:28.260
is dig into our data.

00:22:28.260 --> 00:22:30.610
And we now actually have
a data science team.

00:22:30.610 --> 00:22:32.170
It's two people.

00:22:32.170 --> 00:22:35.840
But that's still
unusual for a nonprofit.

00:22:35.840 --> 00:22:37.920
And our attitude is
we've got, we believe,

00:22:37.920 --> 00:22:42.150
the most innovative teachers in
the United States on our site.

00:22:42.150 --> 00:22:44.510
And they're requesting
resources for their classroom.

00:22:44.510 --> 00:22:45.650
And like I said
before, sometimes it's

00:22:45.650 --> 00:22:47.316
critical stuff they
should have already.

00:22:47.316 --> 00:22:50.410
And sometimes, often, it's
outside of the box stuff.

00:22:50.410 --> 00:22:52.310
These teachers are
ahead of the curve.

00:22:52.310 --> 00:22:54.217
And they're asking
for certain things

00:22:54.217 --> 00:22:56.425
to teach math, or certain
things to teach technology,

00:22:56.425 --> 00:22:59.565
or literacy, that they're
ahead of other teachers.

00:22:59.565 --> 00:23:01.190
And they may be ahead
of budget makers.

00:23:01.190 --> 00:23:04.590
So our first foray into
this is, and still very much

00:23:04.590 --> 00:23:10.430
at the beginning an experiment,
is to dig into that data,

00:23:10.430 --> 00:23:13.150
and say, what are our
teachers telling us?

00:23:13.150 --> 00:23:15.850
And what trends are we seeing?

00:23:15.850 --> 00:23:18.960
And I'll give you
a simple example.

00:23:18.960 --> 00:23:21.810
For a while, there's been a
long push towards, for example,

00:23:21.810 --> 00:23:22.800
Smart Boards.

00:23:22.800 --> 00:23:25.140
And Smart Boards are great.

00:23:25.140 --> 00:23:27.210
But they're also
quite expensive.

00:23:27.210 --> 00:23:29.735
And what we've seen
more often requested

00:23:29.735 --> 00:23:33.290
are what are called
ELMO projectors.

00:23:33.290 --> 00:23:34.917
It's basically the
modern overhead.

00:23:34.917 --> 00:23:37.000
So many of us grew up with
a traditional overhead.

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:39.500
And this is the modern one where
you can put anything on it,

00:23:39.500 --> 00:23:41.377
you can plug in your
computer, et cetera.

00:23:41.377 --> 00:23:43.460
And these are on the order
of hundreds of dollars.

00:23:43.460 --> 00:23:45.170
So this is just a
very simple example,

00:23:45.170 --> 00:23:47.370
where we see teachers
saying, well,

00:23:47.370 --> 00:23:49.310
given a choice between
these technologies,

00:23:49.310 --> 00:23:51.800
I'm going to go for
this cheaper one.

00:23:51.800 --> 00:23:55.480
And Smart Boards
are still awesome.

00:23:55.480 --> 00:23:57.560
And this can be
informative in many ways.

00:23:57.560 --> 00:23:58.890
So maybe we can impact budgets.

00:23:58.890 --> 00:24:00.630
Maybe we can impact policy.

00:24:00.630 --> 00:24:04.114
Maybe we can show
mainstream teachers

00:24:04.114 --> 00:24:06.655
what these teachers who are out
in front, what they're doing,

00:24:06.655 --> 00:24:07.929
and kind of pass that down.

00:24:07.929 --> 00:24:10.220
DIANE SOLINGER: That's kind
of what I was going to ask.

00:24:10.220 --> 00:24:11.845
TIM FERRISS: Well,
let me jump in, too.

00:24:11.845 --> 00:24:13.790
So you guys understand
the power of data.

00:24:13.790 --> 00:24:15.290
Or put a different
way, data when

00:24:15.290 --> 00:24:19.396
you're able to convert it
into meaningful information.

00:24:19.396 --> 00:24:21.020
So I'm going to take
it a step further.

00:24:21.020 --> 00:24:23.030
Hypothetically, this
is not a conversation

00:24:23.030 --> 00:24:24.590
I've had with DonorsChoose.

00:24:24.590 --> 00:24:27.428
OLIVER HURT-HILLER:
Let's do it now.

00:24:27.428 --> 00:24:32.872
TIM FERRISS: The views are my
own [INAUDIBLE] say on Twitter.

00:24:32.872 --> 00:24:34.847
Hypothetically, what happens?

00:24:34.847 --> 00:24:35.430
You have data.

00:24:35.430 --> 00:24:37.710
You have information
on what types of things

00:24:37.710 --> 00:24:39.810
are needed in which districts.

00:24:39.810 --> 00:24:41.300
OK.

00:24:41.300 --> 00:24:44.700
People, generally, in
a given county, state,

00:24:44.700 --> 00:24:46.710
they want their education
to be really good.

00:24:46.710 --> 00:24:50.350
So what happens when you have a
handful of politicians running,

00:24:50.350 --> 00:24:52.016
some of them for
re-election, and you're

00:24:52.016 --> 00:24:55.360
able to say, wow,
that district really

00:24:55.360 --> 00:24:57.310
sucks for these
following things.

00:24:57.310 --> 00:24:59.600
You're just not taking
care of your educators.

00:24:59.600 --> 00:25:03.190
And, hypothetically,
you would have the data

00:25:03.190 --> 00:25:06.130
to be able to apply,
again, this sort

00:25:06.130 --> 00:25:09.470
of karma-cly positive
pressure to say, hey,

00:25:09.470 --> 00:25:11.339
if you look at all
these 10 counties,

00:25:11.339 --> 00:25:13.380
here are the three that
are the worst performing.

00:25:13.380 --> 00:25:14.963
You want to get
re-elected, you better

00:25:14.963 --> 00:25:18.670
propose a solution
that addresses that.

00:25:18.670 --> 00:25:21.470
So it's a very powerful
data set that I

00:25:21.470 --> 00:25:26.150
think could be harnessed at some
point, hypothetically speaking.

00:25:26.150 --> 00:25:28.110
Tactically, I just
want to just touch

00:25:28.110 --> 00:25:30.390
on a couple super
tactical things.

00:25:30.390 --> 00:25:34.216
So there are a handful of really
effective nonprofits out there.

00:25:34.216 --> 00:25:38.210
If you give to any
nonprofit-- of course,

00:25:38.210 --> 00:25:40.235
I would hope that you
give a chunk, at least,

00:25:40.235 --> 00:25:44.210
to DonorsChoose.org because
they make such good use of it.

00:25:44.210 --> 00:25:46.130
A couple things,
number one is take

00:25:46.130 --> 00:25:48.830
advantage of the
matching, no-brainer.

00:25:48.830 --> 00:25:51.550
So one thing that I do every
year, I do $100,000 birthday

00:25:51.550 --> 00:25:54.205
give back, where I say,
hey, I will match up

00:25:54.205 --> 00:26:00.440
to $50,000 whatever you guys
can raise on this project page.

00:26:00.440 --> 00:26:02.739
And my readers always hit it.

00:26:02.739 --> 00:26:04.530
But how can you make
that more interesting?

00:26:04.530 --> 00:26:07.270
You can make it more
interesting if I say,

00:26:07.270 --> 00:26:12.639
instead of donating $1,000 in
cash, donate $1,000 in stock.

00:26:12.639 --> 00:26:14.930
So there are a couple different
ways that's beneficial.

00:26:14.930 --> 00:26:18.200
So you can either have
Google match, which is great.

00:26:18.200 --> 00:26:19.970
You can also, in
an ideal world--

00:26:19.970 --> 00:26:21.870
I'm not sure this is
mechanically possibly.

00:26:21.870 --> 00:26:24.610
But you donate stock,
what does that mean?

00:26:24.610 --> 00:26:28.750
So instead of selling your stock
for $100, paying $30 in tax,

00:26:28.750 --> 00:26:31.938
then donating $70, you
donate 100% of that value

00:26:31.938 --> 00:26:33.570
to the nonprofit.

00:26:33.570 --> 00:26:35.820
I never realized this until
like a year or two ago.

00:26:35.820 --> 00:26:37.410
Because people don't explain it.

00:26:37.410 --> 00:26:40.630
It's just, God, that's
such an obvious thing.

00:26:40.630 --> 00:26:42.320
And so many people
do not realize it,

00:26:42.320 --> 00:26:44.230
because it's very
seldom explained.

00:26:44.230 --> 00:26:44.997
OLIVER HURT-HILLER:
How the match

00:26:44.997 --> 00:26:46.122
would work with that, guys.

00:26:46.122 --> 00:26:48.735
Is we would match the cash
value of what you transferred.

00:26:48.735 --> 00:26:49.610
TIM FERRISS: Perfect.

00:26:49.610 --> 00:26:51.456
OLIVER HURT-HILLER: Oh, wow.

00:26:51.456 --> 00:26:52.664
DIANE SOLINGER: Up to $6,000.

00:26:52.664 --> 00:26:54.538
TIM FERRISS: So if you
have the option, then,

00:26:54.538 --> 00:26:57.860
you make the stock donation
instead of the cash donation.

00:26:57.860 --> 00:26:59.110
Why?

00:26:59.110 --> 00:27:01.820
Because not only are you
giving more to the nonprofit

00:27:01.820 --> 00:27:04.406
if you look at certain
aspects of taxation.

00:27:04.406 --> 00:27:07.870
You get 100% of the
write-off value, also.

00:27:07.870 --> 00:27:09.950
So, anyway, just
super tactically,

00:27:09.950 --> 00:27:11.510
I would say, get
depreciated stock,

00:27:11.510 --> 00:27:13.407
it's a fantastic way to go.

00:27:13.407 --> 00:27:15.740
Especially that it's going
to matched for the cash value

00:27:15.740 --> 00:27:19.959
by this wonderful organization
I've heard of called Google.

00:27:19.959 --> 00:27:21.750
DIANE SOLINGER: Final
question for you guys

00:27:21.750 --> 00:27:24.460
before we transition
a little bit.

