no funny business.

00:28:41.845 --> 00:28:45.187
Remind me where we were.

00:28:45.187 --> 00:28:46.020
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:28:46.020 --> 00:28:46.903
DIANE SOLINGER: You said the
marketplace is giving you

00:28:46.903 --> 00:28:47.064
the information.

00:28:47.064 --> 00:28:49.470
OLIVER HURT-HILLER: Right,
so the teachers are already,

00:28:49.470 --> 00:28:53.440
on sort of a per project basis,
learning from each other.

00:28:53.440 --> 00:28:57.710
But I think one opportunity that
we haven't really exploited,

00:28:57.710 --> 00:29:00.460
which is real exciting
to me, is what

00:29:00.460 --> 00:29:04.960
do you do if you have the most
innovative teachers in America

00:29:04.960 --> 00:29:07.360
all on one website or service.

00:29:07.360 --> 00:29:11.459
And a lot of people have, should
I be sharing lesson plans?

00:29:11.459 --> 00:29:12.750
Should I be sharing curriculum?

00:29:12.750 --> 00:29:15.400
Should they just be supporting
each other in an emotional way?

00:29:15.400 --> 00:29:16.765
Because the truth is,
it's a lonely profession.

00:29:16.765 --> 00:29:18.980
They spend most of their days
not with their colleagues.

00:29:18.980 --> 00:29:20.285
