others into the fold

00:58:46.430 --> 00:58:48.152
in the first week
of December when

00:58:48.152 --> 00:58:50.802
the G Give campaigns happen.

00:58:50.802 --> 00:58:52.510
TIM FERRISS: Just to
reiterate something.

00:58:52.510 --> 00:58:54.343
It's not about the
amount of money you give.

00:58:54.343 --> 00:58:56.680
It's about seeing the
direct result of the dollars

00:58:56.680 --> 00:58:58.672
that you choose to put in.

00:58:58.672 --> 00:59:02.158
So I think, whether it's
Apple's organization,

00:59:02.158 --> 00:59:04.767
or DonorsChoose.org,
just see if you

00:59:04.767 --> 00:59:08.340
can find a specific initiative
that reminds you of a teacher

00:59:08.340 --> 00:59:12.340
or class that led you to doing
this as opposed to flat lining

00:59:12.340 --> 00:59:14.910
or dropping like I'm
sure people have seen

00:59:14.910 --> 00:59:16.717
their classmates suffer from.

00:59:16.717 --> 00:59:19.846
Take the baby steps.

00:59:19.846 --> 00:59:22.560
And we also hear
often from students

00:59:22.560 --> 00:59:25.220
who its' really moving.

00:59:25.220 --> 00:59:29.350
They're floored that a
stranger would help them.

00:59:29.350 --> 00:59:31.472
And the way our
site works is they

00:59:31.472 --> 00:59:32.930
don't know how much
money you gave,

00:59:32.930 --> 00:59:35.150
whether it was $5,
or $50, or $500.

00:59:35.150 --> 00:59:36.275
But you do leave a message.

00:59:36.275 --> 00:59:37.524
You put your picture up there.

00:59:37.524 --> 00:59:38.680
And you leave a message.

00:59:38.680 --> 00:59:40.080
AUDIENCE: Lots of letters.

00:59:40.080 --> 00:59:42.274
OLIVER HURST-HILLER:
You get letters back.

00:59:42.274 --> 00:59:45.100
DIANE SOLINGER: That's
like Apple and his Dad.

00:59:45.100 --> 00:59:46.732
He wrote the letters back.

00:59:46.732 --> 00:59:47.940
So that personal connection--

00:59:47.940 --> 00:59:49.180
OLIVER HURST-HILLER: It's
ultimately about people.

00:59:49.180 --> 00:59:51.250
And that's, I think,
this very human thing

00:59:51.250 --> 00:59:53.770
that probably goes
back tens of hundreds--

00:59:53.770 --> 00:59:57.799
it's like in our DNA
to help each other.

00:59:57.799 --> 00:59:59.840
And when these students
are on the receiving end,

00:59:59.840 --> 01:00:02.540
they say, my gosh, these
strangers did this for me.

01:00:02.540 --> 01:00:03.799
It's quite powerful.

01:00:03.799 --> 01:00:05.590
TIM FERRISS: I had too
much caffeine today.

01:00:05.590 --> 01:00:07.310
But just one more thing.

01:00:07.310 --> 01:00:09.320
It's not just about
helping people.

01:00:09.320 --> 01:00:12.560
Because help, I think--
it's about enabling people.

01:00:12.560 --> 01:00:16.465
It's about trying to level
the playing field a bit

01:00:16.465 --> 01:00:18.540
by giving them the
tools that they

01:00:18.540 --> 01:00:22.540
need to be the highest
version of themselves.

01:00:22.540 --> 01:00:25.260
It's not a handout, specifically
with both these orgs.

01:00:25.260 --> 01:00:26.930
You're teaching
me with the code.

01:00:26.930 --> 01:00:29.770
You're helping people
to acquire a skill,

01:00:29.770 --> 01:00:33.150
whether that be something that
will return dividends forever

01:00:33.150 --> 01:00:35.237
in music, or STEM, or elsewhere.

01:00:35.237 --> 01:00:37.070
You're enabling them,
not just helping them.

01:00:37.070 --> 01:00:38.870
I think it's helpful to
think of it this way.

01:00:38.870 --> 01:00:40.970
OLIVER HURST-HILLER: That's
the power of education.

01:00:40.970 --> 01:00:41.870
DIANE SOLINGER:
Thanks everybody.

01:00:41.870 --> 01:00:43.495
And they'll be around
for a few minutes

01:00:43.495 --> 01:00:45.170
if you want to
ask the questions.

